\paperw12240\paperh15840\margl1800\margr1800\margt1440\margb1440\f0\fs24\cf0
\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 No one spoke as they made their escape through Shulgi\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s dark passages. Or at least, if anyone did speak, Mandri did not hear them. His senses were nearer his skin. His toes squeezed inside his shoes. His palm tingled whenever he braced himself against the cold stone. His legs moved without effort. His seemed like someone else\u8217\'92s. He had to strain to reassert himself inside his head and swivel his eyes down to study the iridescent threads of purpose which guided him through the dark. It was so much effort that he did it once and never again. It was much more pleasant to succumb to this sense of losing control. It did not matter much if he saw where he was going.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 A sense of suspicion followed him, coming from Ayram. The giant gripped his spud-bar spear a little too tightly. He walked a little too far behind, half-hiding behind cover. Mandri briefly wondered if he might be projecting his own paranoia onto the man, but then his stomach growled.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He realized, then, that he was in a bit of trouble.  He needed to eat. But, given recent events, that seemed like a very dangerous thing for him to do.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 he emerged into the desert night.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The twinkling sky above the crater\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s rim was a magnificent blue. The clean air was invigorating. He stood up, brushed off the grit which clung to his sleeves and knees, and then he closed his eyes and took a deep, deep breath. Soreness wrecked his body. It would have bulled him over if he weren\u8217\'92t dwelling in his own periphery.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We shouldn\u8217\'92t stop here,\u8221\'94 Pyetle said as he eyed the night air with suspicion. \u8220\'93We should put as much distance between us and this place as possible.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 torch}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Out of the way,\u8221\'94 Moto grumbled as he pulled himself out of the lizard hole.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 When Moto was all the way out and standing, he took a deep breath, just as Mandri had done.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92ll light a fire,\u8221\'94 a Vessel said.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Long stalks of woody haggas weed grew out of stone-cracks nearby, and Moto gathered these while. Once out, Ayram, wary of Mandri, kept close to him, watched him. Mandri wanted to laugh at the tension, but somehow, he couldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t. He simply stood there, staring at Ayram\u8217\'92s Spark like a freak. Then he watched Pyetle wiggle out of the hole. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Moto a respectable little fire going, having lucked into finding a few bone-dry branches from trees who\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d lived and died in a completely different age.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram permitted them all to sit.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle retrieved from his robes two small bricks of cappash\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 a dried and minced lizard meat spiced with bitter herbs and caked in yellowed fat. He handed one of these to Mandri. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You look like you need it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Whatever force controlling Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s body accepted the offering. He nibbled on a corner, thinking there\u8217\'92d be no taste. At first there wasn\u8217\'92t, but with the second chew the meat\u8217\'92s smoky flavor percolated into being. Every swallow slumped him further into his body\u8217\'92s exhaustion. Somehow the act of eating was pulling him back into his being.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It was not entirely enjoyable.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Sol\u8217\'92s light, I\u8217\'92m tired,\u8221\'94 he mumbled between mouthfuls. \u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t suppose we could take some time to sleep?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No sleep,\u8221\'94 said Ayram, who wasn\u8217\'92t eating anything. He sat cross-legged, appreciating the fire between them. His great spear was stuck into the stone. \u8220\'93We must talk.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri licked his teeth and said, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I know.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle sat to his left. Moto his right. The surviving Vessels hovered around in the space. They all watched with fascination as Ayram raised Pel\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s stomach up by its neck.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Schisol\u8217\'92s own shadow named you the Burshageet.\u8221\'94 he said to Mandri. \u8220\'93Do you know why?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri shook his head.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram paused to let the accusation breathe, because now that it was out the air it was its own kind of beast. It had horns. It to be dealt with.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I understand how you feel,\u8221\'94 Mandri said, or rather, he seemed to say. The sound of his voice was so distant that he wasn\u8217\'92t sure if he\u8217\'92d even spoken the words out loud. But he must have, for Ayram\u8217\'92s lips drew tight, and Moto groaned in frustration.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93None of this matters!\u8221\'94 Moto implored. \u8220\'93Let it all burn. We are }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 done}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 .\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I fear that this will not be done until he is dead.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He remembered that he still had Elrahet\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s knife, so he took it out. Now he was confronted with a decision: should he cut that hungry thread?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Was such a thing even possible?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He could cut it, yes, but would it not grow right back?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Then he noticed another thread, this one thin, almost imperceptible. It branched off that hungry thread and was stuck to the edge of his knife, introducing an uncomfortable contradiction, because now two different futures were outlined here and they couldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t both be true. One demanded he swallow, and the other demanded he didn\u8217\'92t.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 It was conceivable then, that he could cut both them out of existence. But how? Did that require another knife, and another thread of fate? Could that third-order thread be cut? And what about these thoughts, the desires themselves? Perhaps even these were being drawn along a predictable curve through a hidden landscape of fate. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0  He looked again upon the Black knife in his hand and watched in amazement as it all splayed out into a circular fan of hands holding knives. Mandri twisted his wrist to cut, and each blade turned in time to cut its neighbor\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s thread, an infinite regress of causes putting an end to their own infinite regress of effects. Only, none of them cut. Each edge slipped past their neighbor\u8217\'92s thread and bent impossibly back around so as to cut their own, a recursive swirl which severed the very notion of comprehensibility.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I\u8217\'92ll have that blade.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93That\u8217\'92s mine.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 A shadow passed over the fire, and suddenly there was Ayram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s massive frame. The giant had his spear an inch away from Mandri\u8217\'92s forehead.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Give it here,\u8221\'94 Ayram said with an outstretched hand, but as Mandri could not move, the giant was forced reached down and take it for himself. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Let\u8217\'92s all calm down,\u8221\'94 Pyetle said, a little ruffled from the excitement. He reached out to try and guide the chisel tip away, but it Ayram\u8217\'92s hands it might as well been held in ston.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Wasn\u8217\'92t your witch a seer?\u8221\'94 Pyetle asked. \u8220\'93You yourself said she chose this end.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yes, and the final act is to kill him!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Did she say that?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93She didn\u8217\'92t need to, it\u8217\'92s obvious.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle scoffed at this assertion. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Let\u8217\'92s think about this,\u8221\'94 he said.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram sat back down, quiet and brooding. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What about the Schisol\u8217\'92s shadow?\u8221\'94 he asked. \u8220\'93That evil witch could read the future, too. Why would she kill herself? I\u8217\'92ll tell you why\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 she saw how her victory was assured}{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 . }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 She disemboweled herself because she knew that }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 he }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 was going to finish her work!\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Pyetle scoffed. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You can\u8217\'92t possibly know that. Maybe she wasn\u8217\'92t a very good seer. She might have thought her demons would overcome him.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Look at who speaks of what they can\u8217\'92t possibly know.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Think of this, \u8221\'94 Pyetle said as he leaned forward, suddenly more interested in his own argument. \u8220\'93Two bulls penned in the same field fight for an entire summer. One day they grew tired of it. They simply stopped. Now, you\u8217\'92ve said these two witches have been fighting each other for\u8230\'85for however long. Ten thousand years? More? Fighting such a futile war, would they care who wins or loses? I can see them growing tired of it, and deciding to let things fall where they may.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Moto scoffed at this suggestion. As did Ayram. The giant grunted and said, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Elrahet would not idly toss aside the sacrifices of everyone she had ever known, just because she was tired.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I would,\u8221\'94 Pyetle said. And now that the odds were against him, he adopted pious airs. \u8220\'93I would do it because young Mandri here is gift from Solraheen, and I have faith that He\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Solraheen is dead,\u8221\'94 Ayram grumbled. \u8220\'93He has nothing to do with this.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Then why does Mandri bear His fire? You all watched him turn back the hordes of Shis. Now you want to murder him for it? He could kill you right this very moment, but he chooses not to! What crime has he committed?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 His question hung in the air unanswered, but Ayram was able to chew his way through this complication. He swipe-flicked his spear through the air to remember its weight before setting its chisel tip to Mandri\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s neck. \u8220\'93Give me a reason not to kill you.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri stared into the soft glow of Ayram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s Spark, then said, \u8220\'93I don\u8217\'92t need to.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Yes, you do.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92re not going to kill me,\u8221\'94 Mandri said. \u8220\'93Not tonight...perhaps tomorrow\u8230\'85I don\u8217\'92t know.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s disdain deepened. He torqued his shoulders, and it seemed for a moment that he really might strike, but there was a thin thread of purpose drawing his spear away. This did not mean that he did not want to do it. It was clear from his unwavering gaze and firmly planted feet that he did.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What if killing Mandri is what evil desires?\u8221\'94 Pyetle asked. \u8220\'93What if that witch called him the Burshageet just to worry you, so that you would kill him, thus ensuring the end of days?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ayram\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s face twisted up. He was unaccustomed to weight of entertaining such ideas, but the logic was brutal\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 if he were to kill Mandri, then he might save or doom the world in equal measure. Or, Mandri could be of no consequence at all. There was no way for him to know.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He finally lowered his spear.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 He stepped back, then sat down.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The rest of that night, they watched the fire burn down to ash. There was a little conversation about what Pyetle was going to do, how he was going to carry news of these events back to Jeket. He wanted to take Mandri with him. Ayram was firmly against this, but he wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t for anything else.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mandri stared into the fire and smiled. It was such an incredible thing to mean such different things to different people. Pyetle saw in him something between a god and a long-lost brother. Ayram wanted to kill him. Moto, still despairing after Moteah, thought he was nothing more than another body around the fire.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I think I\u8217\'92ll go back to Meskalim,\u8221\'94 Mandri said. \u8220\'93I want to do something about this nasty leech farm out there.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93A leech farm!?\u8221\'94 Pyetle. \u8220\'93Mandri, there are more important problems you could be solving. Come with me to Jeket and I will\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No,\u8221\'94 Mandri said. \u8220\'93I feel convicted. I\u8217\'92m going to do something about that damned farm.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93But there\u8217\'92s\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93One thing at a time.\u8221\'94 Sighing at the realization of the monstrous task. \u8220\'93One thing at a time.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0}